@martinthomson Yeah, compression was what I was referring with "delta ClientHello". You could imagine a ClientHello-specific compression that knows how to toss extensions around (in which case, yeah, it starts getting closer to ESNI transformation), or some more generic delta encoding. Here's an ad hoc goofy thing:

```
enum { bytes(0), reference(1) } FragmentType;
 
struct {
  uint24 offset;
  uint24 length;
} ReferenceFragment;
 
opaque BytesFragment<1..2^24-1>;
 
struct {
  FragmentType type;
  select (Fragment.type) {
    // Append these bytes.
    case bytes: BytesFragment;
    // Append the referenced fragment of the outer ClientHello.
    case reference: ReferenceFragment;
  }
} Fragment;
 
struct {
  // Included so preallocating the buffer and enforcing size limits is easy.
  uint24 clienthello_length;
  // Walk over all the fragments to reconstruct the ClientHello.
  Fragment clienthello_fragments<0..2^24-1>;
} ESNIPlaintext;
```

A ClientHello-specific encoding is easier to produce since senders know how their ClientHellos look like and we can tailor things what fields should and shouldn't be copied. But it's harder to decode since you need to add checks for silly questions like "what order do I insert extensions?" or "what happens if the placeholder is missing" or "what happens if there are two placeholders?" or "what happens if the outer ClientHello is missing the extension to copy?".

Conversely, though it may take more spec text to describe, a bytes-based encoding is easier to decode since you just blindly evaluate the two opcodes and only need to include a couple of checks. But it's harder to encode since you need to account for length prefixes when chopping things up.

We should probably table this until we figure out the padding strategy. (Apparently that's still up in the air!) It also occurs to me that the first bullet in this list is obsolete -- we don't have a named group anymore or padded_length anymore:

```
      struct {
          CipherSuite suite;
          opaque record_digest<0..2^16-1>;
          opaque enc<1..2^16-1>;
          opaque encrypted_ch<1..2^16-1>;
      } ClientEncryptedCH;
```

Can we just say something like the following? 

"Set the "suite" field to a supported cipher suite. This selection SHOULD vary to exercise all supported configurations, but MAY be constant for successive connections to the same server in the same session."

@martinthomson I'll remove the last sentence, not because of v6 (which I do think is a good example), but because it can probably bite us in the future when someone does turn it into a threat. :)

On the latter points, how about the following:

The cost of this type of attack scales linearly with the desired number of target clients. DNS caching behavior makes targeting individual users for extended periods of time, e.g., using per-client ECHOConfig structures delivered via HTTPSSVC RRs with high TTLs, challenging. Moreover, clients can flush any ECHOConfig state upon changing networks to mitigate potential linkability problems.
